This was a good course and I did learn a few things, although I will say it felt pretty entry-level. If you are familiar with a lot of social media channels, then it will be covering a lot of basics. However, it does cover topics such as creating SMART goals for marketing campaigns, measuring your progress through KPIs, and creating a consumer profile and journey to better target those campaigns. Still skimming the surface. I wouldn't say I'm ready to start working as a social media manager quite yet, but hoping I will feel more equipped as I work my way through the rest of the modules.

If you are expecting a more in depth course that teaches the nitty gritty of Facebook ads management for a successful social media campaign, this is not the one. And if you have some experience in marketing, this will be pretty basic.But if you are new to social media marketing, this course covers a more macro understanding of the top social media platforms, how to choose which works best your brand. The course basically teaches you the proper way to draft and start any social media plan.

This is a pretty good overview of the Social Media landscape and the basics of social media marketing. However, it was created by Facebook, and it omits relevant information that would make the company look bad. For example, while they correctly point out that Facebook has more daily active users than any other social media site, they choose not to tell you that the organic reach for a companies Facebook post is only about 6% of it's page likes, and you'll have to pay to boost any post in order for Facebook marketing to have any real effect. Again, it's a well put together intro course, but take it with a grain of salt.

The peer-graded assignments are not a particularly effective method of learning in my opinion since majority of us are students of the course and we're not exactly qualified to be grading each other. We might be giving each other full grades and encouraging mistakes or misunderstandings as a result. It would be better if the assignments were graded by instructors of the course or other professionals whom we can trust to be qualified enough to give us real, beneficial constructive criticism/feedback. Either that or have it as a guided project or optional assignment of some sort. I'm not brimming with ideas at the moment but I hope you understand my concern.

This course provides an excellent opportunity to learn more about the social media environment and how it can integrate with any business. If you're an avid social media user or completely new to social media, this course offers information of value. If you can spend more time (weekly) than suggested, it feels more cohesive. Here are two pieces of constructive feedback I can offer the course creators: Though it's great that anyone can take this course, I think for some people there is a language barrier. The course could provide a better learning experience for all students if Coursera offered subtitles for students whose first language is not English. It seems like everyone does their best to peer-grade on content, but the language barrier can make it difficult to grade other students' work effectively.Finally, I would set higher standards for peer-grading, including a required minimum 100-word comment, offering the currently suggested content (constructive criticism, a question, compliment, etc). Thank you for an excellent online course experience with Coursera, Facebook, and Professor Audenaert.

With people taking the class from all over the world there might be language barriers for some students so their assignments were poor.  Incomplete, didn't follow directions, hastily put together, incoherent, etc.  Then I think about that those same students are grading other people's work. There are a lot of mods but didn't really see them active in the forums answering the questions of students.
